Package sailpoint.connector

Class JDBCConnector

  • java.lang.Object
    • sailpoint.connector.CollectorServices
      • sailpoint.connector.AbstractConnector
        • sailpoint.connector.JDBCConnector
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Connector
    public class JDBCConnector
extends AbstractConnector
    A connector that can be used to read data from JDBC enabled database engines.

    This connector using configuration options to drive the data that is fetched from the database.

    For simple single table implementations the schema can be used exclusively to configure the connector. The native ObjectType in the schema defines the table name when generating the sql.

    For more complex situations the sql can manually be assigned using the sql configuration parameter. CONFIG_SQL_STATEMENT The select statement for the statement will drive the ResultSet that is returned from the query. For each ResultSet returned by the sql a buildMap rule is called to transform the ResultSet into a Map object. The buildMap is where all of the per row transformations can take place and there is a default static method buildMapFromResultSet(ResultSet) that can be called from rules to transform the data into a Map.

    Once each row has been transformed into a Map object it is then transformed to a ResourceObject which is used to represent each unique user or group in the data source.

    The default methods use the Application's Schema to coerce the sql datatype values into our simple Boolean, String, Long, Integer and Date values. These behaviors can be overridden using the Connector.CONFIG_TRANSFORMATION_RULE configuration item.

    See Also:
    buildMapFromResultSet(ResultSet)

        public static final java.lang.String CONFIG_STATEMENT_FETCH_SIZE
        An optional setting that can be specified to override a JDBC connector's default row pre-fetch. For example, Oracle's JDBC driver's default pre- fetch is 10 rows. Other JDBC drivers may have different values. An Application might want to change this depending on the size of data coming from the remote system (row size in bytes) or other factors.       • assembleObject

        protected ResourceObject assembleObject​(Schema schema,
                                        java.sql.ResultSet result,
                                        java.sql.Connection conn,
                                        java.util.Map<java.lang.String,​java.lang.Object> ruleState,
                                        java.lang.String last)
                                 throws ConnectorException
        Assemble a resource object from the ResultSet. This will include, merging objects if necessary. This is interesting since it may be called by getObject or by the iterator. Changes done for Bug - CONNAMDANG-690 (CONETN-318) - According to this bug merging was not working for the JDBC driver whose scroll property is set to TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY. In case of TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY resultSet, the driver can not move back. Or resultset.previous() call will give error, hence merging was not happening. Previous logic was creating two maps, map1 and map2 whenever records with same indexes comes. If the record don't have same index, it means we are done with getting details of record having same index. Then result set cursor is moved to the previous record, because the result.next() call had moved the cursor one record ahead. To resolve this , the next object of result set is stored in a global map with name lastRoMap. With the changes, instead of calling resultset.previous(), the last record is stored in a map lastRoMap. When ever the result.next() is called, map1 will be populated with lastRoMap, and map2 will be populated with next record of same user. Map2 needs to get populated only if map1 is populated by latRoMap. Other wise map2 need not to be called. This check is done with help of a boolean variable _bStoreNextResultInMap; This way the result.nex() will move to end, and finally the last record will be stored in lastRoMap, which is filled in map when the while loop end and returned as a resourceObject.
        Parameters:
        schema - - Object schema like account, group etc.
        result - - Database resultSet.
        ruleState - - A variable used by buildMap rule to find the valid state of rule.
        last - - Last identity in the resultSet.
        Returns:
        - returns resourceObject
        Throws:
        ConnectorException

      • buildMapFromResultSet

        public static java.util.Map<java.lang.String,​java.lang.Object> buildMapFromResultSet​(java.sql.ResultSet result)
                                                                                    throws ConnectorException
        Given a ResultSet, for each of the column names put a new key/value pair into the map that represents the results set column value.

        There will be a key for each of the values selected in the SQL. This code builds the column names using the ResultSet's meta-data object (ResultSetMetaData).

        This method is typically the first method that is called in a buildMap rule to build a base map that can then be altered to suite a customers needs.

        Each call to the jdbc build map rule is handed several things including and attribute named 'result' that represents the JDBC ResultSet for each row returned from the sql query. 

            
     // Here is an example of how it might be used in a buildmap
     // rule
     Map defaultMap = JDBCConnector.buildMapFromResultSet(result);
     // make your customizations/transformations               
          
     return defaultMap;
        Returns:
        Map representing the ResultSet or null if there are no columns with values in the result.
        Throws:
        ConnectorException
        Since:
        1.5, 5.1
        See Also:
        ResultSetMetaData
